In the XPS analysis, the N 1s, O 1s, and C 1s peaks were found in the spectra of both CDs and Cu(II)-CDs NPs-6 (Fig. 4
                        a), while the Cu 2p peaks appeared in the Cu(II)-CDs NPs-6. Compared with the CDs, the surface C, N, and O atomic concentrations did not change significantly in the Cu(II)-CDs NPs-6 while Cu appeared with a low surface atomic concentration (Table 2
                        ). The surface Cu atomic concentration in the Cu(II)-CDs NPs-6 was obviously lower than the ICP-OES result (33.29%), indicating that Cu(II) ions was mainly distributed in the internal structure of the fabricated nanoparticles. Besides, the Cu 2p spectrum could be deconvoluted into two main peaks at 931.5 and 951.5 eV, as well as two satellite peaks at 941.3 and 960.1 eV (Fig. 4b) corresponding to Cu(II) in the paramagnetic chemical state [18], revealing the formation of the coordination bonds between Cu(II) ions and carboxylic groups in CDs.
